{
  "answer": "In Mirza Ghalib's ghazal \"Hazaaron khwahishein aisi ke har khwahish pe dam nikle,\" the famous couplet **Mohabbat mein nahin hai farq jeene aur marne ka / Usi ko dekh kar jeete hain jis kaafir pe dam nikle** expresses the lover's profound indifference to the boundary between life and death.[^1] The lover lives solely through the act of gazing upon his beloved (likened to an \"infidel\" or cruel figure whose beauty is spiritually perilous), yet that very gaze is the cause of his demise—his breath (dam) expires upon her. Thus, life and death merge inseparably in love: sustaining vitality and delivering mortality are one and the same, rendering the distinction meaningless. The lover achieves a state of utter surrender, where survival depends on the object that destroys him, embodying love's paradoxical transcendence over earthly dualities.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, chapter 70 (\"Hazaaron khwahishein aisi ke har khwahish pe dam nikle\"), transliteration, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/70-hazaaron-khwahishein-aisi-ke-har-khwahish-pe-dam-n/transliteration/#p-f74c89).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, chapter 70 (\"Hazaaron khwahishein aisi ke har khwahish pe dam nikle\"), translation, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/70-hazaaron-khwahishein-aisi-ke-har-khwahish-pe-dam-n/translation/#p-d832fa).",
